1:25 scale STLs of the concrete castle printed by Andrey Rudenko (http://www.totalkustom.com/) on his 3D House Printer. Castle design by Misha Tikh, printed by Andrey Rudenko. From Andrey: It has been two years since I first began toying with the idea of a 3D printer that was capable of constructing homes. In my vision of using 3D printers as new technology, I wanted a light, portable, and stable machine. First, I built a small 3D printer that used plastic for its main material, and from that, I started experimenting on enlarging the printer and using variations of cement mixes. Layering cement was an extremely difficult task- it required extensive tuning of the printer on a programming level, as well as using exact quantities for the cement mix. While testing the printer, I ran into obstacles (such as the nightmare of the extruder clogging) and discovered even further abilities of the printer, like that it can print much more than 50cm a day as I originally thought. I was able to calibrate the machine so that it prints nearly perfect layers now, and I played with various heights and widths of the cement layers. My current standard is 10 millimeters in height by 30 millimeters in width, but countless other options are available with just the click of a button.
​
This two year long journey has led me to build the world’s first 3D Printed Concrete Castle. Finally, it stands! Read more here:
http://www.totalkustom.com/3d-castle-completed.html

Print all assembled with supports, or print towers separately then glue to the top of the castle walls.  
Fun fact: It took seven guys and a lot of improvised rigging to lift the largest tower to its location on top of the wall!

description.text:
The original thing this derives from was a bit hard to print.  Because of the placement of the integral balls, it required a lot of support material, no matter what the orientation.
This thing prints the Yazzonic Disc Balls OnIt in separate pieces.  There is the basic disc, which now has little ball grabbing protrusions, and then there are the separate balls, which are specifically designed to slip over the disc, and be held in place by the protrusions.
As you can see in the picture, having this particular structure gives you many options in terms of connecting to the other pieces of the Yazzo system.
Also, this particular default design can take 1/2" wooden beads as well.  They fit snugly between the grabbing protrusions, so you have some options as to how you might want to use this thing.

1) Print a few discs
2) Print enough balls to fit in discs
3) Fit balls into discs
4) Rejoice! The fit of the balls into the disc is very snug. The first two will go in easily, and you will have to work hard to get the last one in. That's by design. If you make it too easy, they won't hold in place very well.

description.text:
I redesigned the z-Homing switches on my Leapfrog Creatr. I always had problems with long term calibration of the z-axis.
The inductive sensor is mounted directly on the extruder carrier. It measures the distance relative to a steel scale on the print bed. The repeatability of the z-Homing is a lot better now.
I added an additional failsafe limit switch in the back, because the inductive one will only be triggered if the y-axis is homed before!.
It really works like a charm. Be sure that you know what you are doing before trying this yourself. You might void your warranty ..

Actually the Creatr electronics board already has an output for the connection of a nozzle cooling fan. The PWM output is located at the innermost terminal of the terminal block, where the heater elements are connected too. The PWM output will just open/close a connection to GND. I used a small step-down module to get a +12V supply for the fan and added a flyback-diode to be an the safe side. An additional fan-attenuator makes the fan run a lot smoother.
This way the fan will be speed controlled according to the "cooling options" of your slicer.

If you have an iPhone and watch long movies (usually from ripped DVDs) leaving the phone in the dock doesn't cut it, the iPhone needs to be horizontal. I usually have CNN, ABC or a few hours of news on my phone and like to leave it on my desk while I work but you can't watch these in the dock since it's turned the wrong way. Long plane / train trips with a tray made me want to make this too.
So - here's an iPhone stand I made, you can take the file to a place like TechShop in SF or anywhere there's a high powered laser that can cut acrylic. Believe it or not there are lots of these lasers in most cities, definitely at a lot of campuses now too. Universal and Epilog are usually the only two brands you'll come across.
I figured this is a good beginner project for getting starting with your own little "FabLab" like project. Variations on this model will work with other phones too, all depends on the size and dimensions of your phone of course.
I made this stand as a snap-to-together / press fit and it can be reproduced cheap, if anyone designs a better version send me the file and I'll post it up here on MAKE. I put a hole on each leg so the USB cable could fit through, it seems to be a better way to hold the sync/power cable.
Here we go... Get some acrylic, I bought a sheet of 12" x 12" clear acrylic (1/8th" thickness). You can get these sheets at local plastic stores in most big cities or online - Link (McMaster-Carr $6.48). Cast (not extruded) tends to be more scratch resistant and better for projects like this.
Download this file, it's an Adobe Illustrator file (black and white vector line art, included are other formats if needed) - Link (ZIP with AI//CDR/DXF). If you want to make a lot of these just copy and past the 2 shapes over and over.
instructions can be found here... http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2007/09/how_to_make_an_iphone_sta.html

I never understood why I was seeing herringbone gears that required an entire extruder upgrade to get them to function so I made these.

.
Getting these gears to mesh is not the easiest of tasks (nature of the beast) but to make sure they are on right both gear's outer most layer must be flush with each other.

title: Gen7 opto-endstop for dual-Extrusion of conductive material

description.text:
This is a proof of concept for creating a fully 3d printed PCB using a dual extrusion setup with ABS for the board and a conductive material (such as wire glue, conductive paint, copper clay, etc..) for the traces. This would of course require a paste extruder for the conductive material.
I haven't tested this yet, but it should work. There are a few variables on the top of the scad file for customization (width of the traces, width of the pads, thickness of the conductive material and board thickness).
If we're able to 3d print a PCB with working traces, then there wouldn't be any need for etching a copper board.
This design is based on the Gen7 opto-endstop design : http://reprap.org/wiki/Gen7_Endstop_1.3.1 and I used the OptoEndstop.pcb file from github (https://github.com/Traumflug/Generation_7_Electronics) for the holes/traces positions.
If this works, then maybe the whole gen7 electronics can be converted : http://reprap.org/wiki/Generation_7_Electronics
A tool for automatic conversion of .pcb files into .scad would be required because doing it by hand is very time consuming.
If someone is able to test this and confirm whether or not it works, then that would be great!
Thanks.

I wanted a mount that had some flexibility. Here is the result, its been tested for a while and so far held well. (Printed in ABS)
Its almost all 3d printed and glued together with acetone slurry.
Other bits are the bolts, the aluminum bush and the washers.

Print all 3 using perimeters of 3, bottom layer of 2 and top layer of 3. Honeycomb infill off 20%.
"Glue" the angles to the base at 90 deg using the acetone slurry.
The parts will be a very tight fit however the acetone will allow them to slot together. Hold parts together for a minute or so.
"glue" the back to the rest of the structure.
I used an aluminum bush between the bolts washer and the mount as not to tighten directly on the ABS material.

title: 35mm Filament mount for Ultimaker 2
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: A filament holder for the Ultimaker 2 with a 35mm base for filament with a smaller diameter hole. The filament holder is ready to be used straight from the printer.

The filament holder was made by redrawing the mount that connects with the Ultimaker 2 from an original Ultimaker 2 filament holder.
A 35mm half circle was then added to allow for a filament spool with a 80mm width.
Finally fillets and supports were added so that the holder only would need support material for printing the mount.
The filament holder requires no additional finishing or parts just remove the support material and you are ready to go. I have included the original Soild Edge part file so that the diameter and width of the filament holder can be adjusted as needed.

title: Angled filament holder for Ultimaker 2 and flex filament
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
An angled filament for the Ultimaker 2 designed for use with flex filament as the current Ultimaker 2 filament holder design can cause the filament to get locked because of its flexibility and the angles between the spool and the feeder.  
The holder is designed for use with original Ultimaker size filament spools.

The filament holder was made by redrawing the mount that connects with the Ultimaker 2 from an original Ultimaker 2 filament holder.   
The holder is designed for use with original Ultimaker size filament spools.  
Finally fillets and supports were added so that the holder only would need support material for printing the mount.   
The filament holder requires no additional finishing or parts just remove the support material and you are ready to go.   
I have included the original Soild Edge part file so that the diameter and width of the filament holder can be adjusted as needed.
